# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acinetactis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acinetactis/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:acinetactis/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:acinetactis/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:acinetactis/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] Born in Stožec, Pascher was the son of a teacher, attended the Gymnasium in Krummau and studied natural science at the German University in Prague, from which he received a doctorate in 1905, and graduated in 1909.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] In 1908, in partnership with Viktor Langhans, he co-founded a Hydrobiological Laboratory in Hirschberg.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] In 1912 he became an associate professor of Herbalism and Cryptogamic Botany, later being promoted to Full Professor in 1927.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] In 1933, he became Director of the Botanical Institutes and Botanical Gardens at the German University in Prague.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] He served as the editor for *Beihefte zum Botanischen Centralblatt* for the last twenty years of his life.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] A German nationalist, he joined the Sudeten German Party in 1938, and following the German Occupation of Czechoslovakia, actively collaborated with the Nazi regime.
[src:acinetactis/adolf-pascher] He committed suicide on 7 May 1945, three days after the end of World War II.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] AlgaeBase began in March 1996, founded by Michael Guiry.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] By 2005, the database contained about 65,000 names.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] In 2013, AlgaeBase and the Flanders Marine Institute (VLIZ) signed an end-user license agreement regarding the Electronic Intellectual Property of AlgaeBase.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] This allows the World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS) to include taxonomic names of algae in WoRMS, thereby allowing WoRMS, as part of the Aphia database, to make its overview of all described marine species more complete.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] After a long phase of further development and testing, the AlgaeBase harvester tool was implemented by the WoRMS data management team in early 2019.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] Since then, newly-added species in AlgaeBase are added to Aphia and, if marine, to WoRMS as well.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] The database is hosted at the National University of Ireland's Ryan Institute, in Galway.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] It includes about all types of algae, as well as one group of flowering plants, the sea-grasses.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] Information about each species' taxonomy, nomenclature and distribution is included, and the algae covered include terrestrial as well as marine and freshwater species, such as seaweeds, phytoplankton, and freshwater algae.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] As of 2019, marine species have the best coverage, including sea-grasses.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] As of 2014 there were nearly 17,000 images, and the database was being used by 2,000–3,000 individual visitors each day.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] As of 2023, there were about 170,000 species and infraspecies in AlgaeBase.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] The synchronisation between AlgaeBase and Aphia was possible through support of the LifeWatch Species Information Backbone.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] LifeWatch, the E-Science European Infrastructure for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Research, is a distributed virtual laboratory, which is used for different aspects of biodiversity research.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] As of 2022, the main sponsors of the database are the Phycological Society of America, the British Phycological Society, the International Phycological Society, and the Korean Phycological Society.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] Programming is carried out by Pier Kuipers and Caoilte Guiry, and Michael Guiry.
[src:acinetactis/algaebase] Jonathan Guthrie was responsible for programming much of earlier versions.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] The cells are generally around 10 μm in length, without any shell or covering.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] They produce filose pseudopods to capture bacteria, but do not use them for locomotion, which usually takes place by gliding along surfaces.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] Most members have two flagella, one directed forward and one trailing under the cell, inserted at right angles near its anterior.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] The nucleus is connected to the flagellar bases and accompanied by a characteristic paranuclear body.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] Genetic studies place the cercomonads among the Cercozoa, a diverse group of amoeboid and flagellate protozoans.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] The classification of genera and species continues to undergo revision.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] Some genera have been merged, like *Cercomonas* and *Cercobodo*.
[src:acinetactis/cercomonas] Others like *Helkesimastix*, *Sainouron* and *Cholamonas* have been moved to Helkesida, while the rest of the family Heteromitidae has been moved to Glissomonadida.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] The group includes most amoeboids and flagellates that feed by means of filose pseudopods.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] These may be restricted to part of the cell surface, but there is never a true cytostome or mouth as found in many other protozoa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] They show a variety of forms and have proven difficult to define in terms of structural characteristics, although their unity is strongly supported by phylogenetic studies.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] As well as being highly diverse in morphology and physiology, Cercozoa also shows high ecological diversity.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] The phylum Cercozoa includes many of the most abundant and ecologically significant protozoa in soil, marine and freshwater ecosystems.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Soil-dwelling cercozoans are one of the dominant groups of free-living eukaryotic microorganisms found in temperate soils, accounting for around 30% of identifiable protozoan DNA in arid or semi-arid soils and 15% in more humid soils.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] In transcriptomic analyses they account for 40-60% of all identifiable protozoan RNA found in forest and grassland soils.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] They also comprise 9-24% of all operational taxonomic units found in the ocean floor.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Some cercozoa are coprophilic or coprozoic, meaning they use feces as a source of nutrients or as transport through animal hosts.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] The faecal habitat is an understudied reservoir of microbial eukaryotic diversity, dominated by amoeboflagellates from the phylum Cercozoa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Strongly coprophilic examples of cercozoa are the flagellates *Cercomonas*, *Proleptomonas* and *Helkesimastix*, and the sorocarpic amoeba *Guttulinopsis*.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Many new cercozoan lineages, especially among sarcomonads, have been discovered through phylogenetic sampling of feces because they appear preferentially in this medium.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Cercozoan bacterivores (i.e. predators of bacteria) are highly diverse and important in the plant phyllosphere, the leaf surfaces of plants.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Particularly sarcomonads, with their ability to cyst, feed and multiply within hours, are perfectly adapted to the fluctuating environmental factors in the phyllosphere.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Their predation causes shifts in the bacterial communities: they reduce populations of alphaproteobacteria and betaproteobacteria, which are less resistant to their grazing, in favour of other bacterial populations such as gammaproteobacteria.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Originally, Cercozoa contained both Filosa and Endomyxa, according to phylogenetic analyses using ribosomal RNA and tubulin.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] These analyses also confirmed Cercozoa as the sister group of Retaria within the supergroup Rhizaria.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] However, the monophyly of the group was still uncertain.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] Posterior multigene phylogenetic analyses consistently found Cercozoa to be paraphyletic, because Endomyxa clustered next to Retaria instead of Filosa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] More recent phylogenomic analyses with better sampling recovered a sister relationship between Filosa (=Cercozoa) and Endomyxa once again.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] It is composed of two subphyla: Filosa and Endomyxa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] On the other hand, Reticulofilosa is probably paraphyletic, with Granofilosea diverging earlier than Chlorarachnea, which makes Chlorarachnea the sister group of Monadofilosa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] A more recent phylogenomic analysis recovered both Monadofilosa and Reticulofilosa as monophyletic within the clade Filosa.
[src:acinetactis/cercozoan] These two orders have been classified as the class Skiomonadea, within Reticulofilosa.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The **Encyclopedia of Life** (**EOL**) is a free, online encyclopedia intended to document all of the 1.9 million living species known to science.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] It aggregates content to form "pages" for every known species.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Content is compiled from existing trusted databases which are curated by experts and it calls on the assistance of non-experts throughout the world.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] It includes video, sound, images, graphics, information on characteristics, as well as text.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] In addition, the Encyclopedia incorporates species-related content from the Biodiversity Heritage Library, which digitizes millions of pages of printed literature from the world's major natural history libraries.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The BHL digital content is indexed with the names of organisms using taxonomic indexing software developed by the Global Names project.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The EOL project was initially backed by a US$50 million funding commitment, led by the MacArthur Foundation and the Sloan Foundation, who provided US$20 million and US$5 million, respectively.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The additional US$25 million came from five cornerstone institutions—the Field Museum, Harvard University, the Marine Biological Laboratory, the Missouri Botanical Garden, and the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The project was initially led by Jim Edwards and the development team by David Patterson.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Today, participating institutions and individual donors continue to support EOL through financial contributions.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL went live on 26 February 2008 with 30,000 entries.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The site relaunched on 5 September 2011 with a redesigned interface and tools.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The new version – referred to as EOLv2 – was developed in response to requests from the general public, citizen scientists, educators and professional biologists for a site that was more engaging, accessible and personal.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] EOLv2 is redesigned to enhance usability and encourage contributions and interactions among users.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] It is also internationalized with interfaces provided for English, German, Spanish, French, Galician, Serbian, Macedonian, Arabic, Chinese, Korean and Ukrainian language speakers.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] On 16 January 2014, *EOL* launched TraitBank, a searchable, open digital repository for organism traits, measurements, interactions and other facts for all taxa.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Information about many species is already available from a variety of sources, in particular about the megafauna.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Gathering currently available data on all 1.9 million species will take about 10 years.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] As of September 2011, EOL had information on more than 700,000 species available, along with more than 600,000 photos and millions of pages of scanned literature.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The initiative relies on indexing information compiled by other efforts, including the Species 2000 and ITIS, Catalogue of Life, Fishbase and the Assembling Tree of Life project of NSF, AmphibiaWeb, Mushroom explorer, micro*scope, etc.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The initial focus has been on living species but will later include extinct species.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] As the discovery of new species is expected to continue (currently at about 20,000 per year), the encyclopedia will continue to grow.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] As taxonomy finds new ways to include species discovered by molecular techniques, the rate of new additions will increase, particularly in respect to the microbial work of (eu)bacteria, archaebacteria and viruses.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL's goal is to serve as a resource for the general public, enthusiastic amateurs, educators, students and professional scientists from around the world.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The Encyclopedia of Life is an aggregative environment, that collects data from other on-line data sources.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] It provides full provenance for information through citations from its trusted databases.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Professional researchers publishing academic research should cite directly to the underlying data.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Users may not currently edit EOL's entries directly but may register for the site to join specialist expert communities to discuss relevant information, questions, possible corrections, sources, and potential updates, contribute images and sound, or volunteer for technical support services.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Its interface is translated at translatewiki.net.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] EOL was made distinctive by its incorporation of 'taxonomic intelligence', a growing array of algorithms that sought to emulate the practices of taxonomists.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] These tools included names resolution so that data entered into different databases using different names for organisms could be combined.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Components of hierarchical classifications systems could be used to drill-down or to expand data searches.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] Common components of different classification schemes were used to allow users to navigate using multiple classifications and to meander among schemes.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] This initiative overcame a major problem of many biological data bases, that of having rigid and singular classification structures that were unable to reflect the diversity of views, or evolving concepts of how names of species and other taxa should be interpreted.
[src:acinetactis/encyclopedia-of-life] The names management systems continue to be developed by the Global Names project.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The **eukaryotes** (/juːˈkærioʊts, -əts/) are the domain **Eukaryota** or **Eukarya**, organisms whose cells have a membrane-bound nucleus.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] All animals, plants, fungi, seaweeds, and many unicellular organisms are eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They constitute a major group of life forms alongside the two groups of prokaryotes: the Bacteria and the Archaea.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes represent a small minority of the number of organisms, but given their generally much larger size, their collective global biomass is much larger than that of prokaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The eukaryotes emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Ignoring mitochondrial DNA (which is bacterial rather than archaeal), this would imply only two domains of life, Bacteria and Archaea, with eukaryotes incorporated among the Archaea.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes first emerged during the Paleoproterozoic, likely as flagellated cells.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The leading evolutionary theory is they were created by symbiogenesis between an anaerobic Promethearchaeota archaeon and an aerobic proteobacterium, which formed the mitochondria.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] A second episode of symbiogenesis with a cyanobacterium created the plants, with chloroplasts.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells contain membrane-bound organelles such as the nucleus, the endoplasmic reticulum, and the Golgi apparatus.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes may be either unicellular or multicellular.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In comparison, prokaryotes are typically unicellular.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Unicellular eukaryotes are sometimes called protists.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes can reproduce both asexually through mitosis and sexually through meiosis and gamete fusion (fertilization).
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The word *eukaryote* is derived from the Greek words "eu" (εὖ) meaning "true" or "good" and "karyon" (κάρυον) meaning "nut" or "kernel", referring to the nucleus of a cell.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are organisms that range from microscopic single cells, such as picozoans under 3 micrometers across, to animals like the blue whale, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 meters (110 ft) long, or plants like the coast redwood, up to 120 meters (390 ft) tall.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Many eukaryotes are unicellular; the informal grouping called protists includes many of these, with some multicellular forms like the giant kelp up to 200 feet (61 m) long.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The multicellular eukaryotes include the animals, plants, and fungi, but again, these groups too contain many unicellular species.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells are typically much larger than those of prokaryotes—the bacteria and the archaea—having a volume of around 10,000 times greater.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes represent a small minority of the number of organisms, but, as many of them are much larger, their collective global biomass (468 gigatons) is far larger than that of prokaryotes (77 gigatons), with plants alone accounting for over 81% of the total biomass of Earth.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The eukaryotes are a diverse lineage, consisting mainly of microscopic organisms.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Multicellularity in some form has evolved independently at least 25 times within the eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Complex multicellular organisms, not counting the aggregation of amoebae to form slime molds, have evolved within only six eukaryotic lineages: animals, symbiomycotan fungi, brown algae, red algae, green algae, and land plants.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are grouped by genomic similarities, so that groups often lack visible shared characteristics.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The defining feature of eukaryotes is that their cells have a well-defined, membrane-bound nucleus, distinguishing them from prokaryotes that lack such a structure.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells have a variety of internal membrane-bound structures, called organelles, and a cytoskeleton which defines the cell's organization and shape.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The nucleus stores the cell's DNA, which is divided into linear bundles called chromosomes; these are separated into two matching sets by a microtubular spindle during nuclear division, in the distinctively eukaryotic process of mitosis.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes differ from prokaryotes in multiple ways, with unique biochemical pathways such as sterane synthesis.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The eukaryotic signature proteins have no homology to proteins in other domains of life, but appear to be universal among eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They include the proteins of the cytoskeleton, the complex transcription machinery, the membrane-sorting systems, the nuclear pore, and some enzymes in the biochemical pathways.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryote cells include a variety of membrane-bound structures, together forming the endomembrane system.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Simple compartments, called vesicles and vacuoles, can form by budding off other membranes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Many cells ingest food and other materials through a process of endocytosis, where the outer membrane invaginates and then pinches off to form a vesicle.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Some cell products can leave in a vesicle through exocytosis.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The nucleus is surrounded by a double membrane known as the nuclear envelope, with nuclear pores that allow material to move in and out.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Various tube- and sheet-like extensions of the nuclear membrane form the endoplasmic reticulum, which is involved in protein transport and maturation.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] It includes the rough endoplasmic reticulum, covered in ribosomes which synthesize proteins; these enter the interior space or lumen.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Subsequently, they generally enter vesicles, which bud off from the smooth endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In most eukaryotes, these protein-carrying vesicles are released and their contents further modified in stacks of flattened vesicles (cisternae), the Golgi apparatus.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Vesicles may be specialized; for instance, lysosomes contain digestive enzymes that break down biomolecules in the cytoplasm.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Mitochondria are organelles in eukaryotic cells.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The mitochondrion is commonly called "the powerhouse of the cell", for its function providing energy by oxidizing sugars or fats to produce the energy-storing molecule ATP.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Mitochondria have two surrounding membranes, each a phospholipid bilayer, the inner of which is folded into invaginations called cristae where aerobic respiration takes place.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Mitochondria contain their own DNA, which has close structural similarities to bacterial DNA, from which it originated, and which encodes rRNA and tRNA genes that produce RNA which is closer in structure to bacterial RNA than to eukaryote RNA.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Some eukaryotes, such as the metamonads *Giardia* and *Trichomonas*, and the amoebozoan *Pelomyxa*, appear to lack mitochondria, but all contain mitochondrion-derived organelles, like hydrogenosomes or mitosomes, having lost their mitochondria secondarily.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They obtain energy by enzymatic action in the cytoplasm.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] It is thought that mitochondria developed from prokaryotic cells which became endosymbionts living inside eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Plants and various groups of algae have plastids as well as mitochondria.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Plastids, like mitochondria, have their own DNA and are developed from endosymbionts, in this case cyanobacteria.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They usually take the form of chloroplasts which, like cyanobacteria, contain chlorophyll and produce organic compounds (such as glucose) through photosynthesis.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Although plastids probably had a single origin, not all plastid-containing groups are closely related.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Instead, some eukaryotes have obtained them from other eukaryotes through secondary endosymbiosis or ingestion.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The capture and sequestering of photosynthetic cells and chloroplasts, kleptoplasty, occurs in many types of modern eukaryotic organisms.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The cytoskeleton provides stiffening structure and points of attachment for motor structures that enable the cell to move, change shape, or transport materials.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The motor structures are microfilaments of actin and actin-binding proteins.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] These include α-actinin, fimbrin, and filamin in submembranous cortical layers and bundles.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Motor proteins of microtubules, dynein and kinesin, and myosin of actin filaments, make the network dynamic.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Many eukaryotes have long slender motile cytoplasmic projections, called flagella, or multiple shorter structures called cilia.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] These organelles are variously involved in movement, feeding, and sensation.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They are composed mainly of tubulin, and are entirely distinct from prokaryotic flagella.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They are supported by a bundle of microtubules arising from a centriole, characteristically arranged as nine doublets surrounding two singlets.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Flagella may have hairs (mastigonemes), as in many stramenopiles.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Their interior is continuous with the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Centrioles are often present, even in cells and groups that do not have flagella, but conifers and flowering plants have neither.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] They generally occur in groups that give rise to various microtubular roots.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] These form a primary component of the cytoskeleton, and are often assembled over the course of several cell divisions, with one flagellum retained from the parent and the other derived from it.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Centrioles produce the spindle during nuclear division.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The cells of plants, algae, fungi and most chromalveolates, but not animals, are surrounded by a cell wall.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] This is a layer outside the cell membrane, providing the cell with structural support, protection, and a filtering mechanism.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The cell wall also prevents over-expansion when water enters the cell.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The major polysaccharides making up the primary cell wall of land plants are cellulose, hemicellulose, and pectin.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The cellulose microfibrils are linked together with hemicellulose, embedded in a pectin matrix.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The most common hemicellulose in the primary cell wall is xyloglucan.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes have a life cycle that involves sexual reproduction, alternating between a haploid phase, where only one copy of each chromosome is present in each cell, and a diploid phase, with two copies of each chromosome in each cell.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] There is considerable variation in this pattern.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Plants have both haploid and diploid multicellular phases.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes have lower metabolic rates and longer generation times than prokaryotes, because they are larger and therefore have a smaller surface area to volume ratio.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The evolution of sexual reproduction may be a primordial characteristic of eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Based on a phylogenetic analysis, Dacks and Roger have proposed that facultative sex was present in the group's common ancestor.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] A core set of genes that function in meiosis is present in both *Trichomonas vaginalis* and *Giardia intestinalis*, two organisms previously thought to be asexual.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Since these two species are descendants of lineages that diverged early from the eukaryotic evolutionary tree, core meiotic genes, and hence sex, were likely present in the common ancestor of eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Species once thought to be asexual, such as *Leishmania* parasites, have a sexual cycle.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Amoebae, previously regarded as asexual, may be anciently sexual; while present-day asexual groups could have arisen recently.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In antiquity, the two lineages of animals and plants were recognized by Aristotle and Theophrastus.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The lineages were given the taxonomic rank of kingdom by Linnaeus in the 18th century.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Though he included the fungi with plants with some reservations, it was later realized that they are quite distinct and warrant a separate kingdom.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The various single-cell eukaryotes were originally placed with plants or animals when they became known.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Goldfuss coined the word *Protozoa* to refer to organisms such as ciliates, and this group was expanded until Ernst Haeckel made it a kingdom encompassing all single-celled eukaryotes, the Protista, in 1866.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The protists were at that time thought to be "primitive forms", and thus an evolutionary grade, united by their primitive unicellular nature.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In 1996, the evolutionary biologist Lynn Margulis proposed to replace kingdoms and domains with "inclusive" names to create a "symbiosis-based phylogeny", giving the description "Eukarya (symbiosis-derived nucleated organisms)".
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] By the early 21st century, a rough consensus started to emerge from phylogenomic studies.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The majority of eukaryotes can be placed in one of two large clades dubbed Amorphea (similar in composition to the unikont hypothesis) and the Diphoda (formerly bikonts), which includes plants and most algal lineages.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] A third major grouping, the Excavata, has been abandoned as a formal group as it was found to be paraphyletic.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The proposed phylogeny below includes two groups of excavates (Discoba and Metamonada), and incorporates the 2021 proposal that picozoans are close relatives of rhodophytes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The Provora are a group of microbial predators discovered in 2022.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] TSAR is a possible clade that would contain Telonemia and the SAR supergroup.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The origin of the eukaryotic cell, or *eukaryogenesis*, is a milestone in the evolution of life, since eukaryotes include all complex cells and almost all multicellular organisms.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The last eukaryotic common ancestor (LECA) is the hypothetical origin of all living eukaryotes, and was most likely a biological population, not a single individual.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The LECA is believed to have been a protist with a nucleus, at least one centriole and flagellum, facultatively aerobic mitochondria, sex (meiosis and syngamy), a dormant cyst with a cell wall of chitin or cellulose, and peroxisomes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] An endosymbiotic union between a motile anaerobic archaean and an aerobic alphaproteobacterium gave rise to the LECA and all eukaryotes with mitochondria.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] A second, much later endosymbiosis with a cyanobacterium gave rise to the ancestor of plants, with chloroplasts.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The presence of eukaryotic biomarkers in archaea points towards an archaeal origin, except for mitochondrial DNA, which is bacterial in origin.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The genomes of Promethearchaeota archaea have plenty of eukaryotic signature protein genes, which play a crucial role in the development of the cytoskeleton and complex cellular structures characteristic of eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In 2022, cryo-electron tomography demonstrated that Promethearchaeota archaea have a complex actin-based cytoskeleton, providing the first direct visual evidence of the archaeal ancestry of eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The timing of the origin of eukaryotes is hard to determine.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Multiple different fossils that may be early eukaryotes have been suggested, but remain contested.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Fossils that are clearly related to modern groups start appearing an estimated 1.2 billion years ago, in the form of red algae, though fossilized Vindhyan filamentous algae have been suggested to be as much as 1.6 to 1.7 billion years old, rather than Cambrian as previously thought.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] A 2026 study suggests that early fossil eukaryotes (1.75-1.4 Gya) may have been benthic aerobes, living on the bottom of oxygenated waters, and may not have colonised planktonic environments until much later, after 1 Gya.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Fossils from the Ruyang Group of China, dating to approximately 1.8-1.6 billion years ago, may be the oldest known eukaryotes.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] One possible earliest multicellular eukaryote fossil is *Qingshania magnifica* from North China, which lived 1.635 billion years ago.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] This would suggest that the crown group eukaryotes originated in the late Paleoproterozoic (Statherian).
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Other early unicellular eukaryotes, *Tappania plana*, *Shuiyousphaeridium macroreticulatum*, *Dictyosphaera macroreticulata*, *Germinosphaera alveolata*, and *Valeria lophostriata* from North China, lived approximately 1.65 billion years ago.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Some acritarchs are known from at least 1.65 billion years ago, and a fossil, *Grypania*, which may be an alga, is as much as 2.1 billion years old.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The "problematic" fossil *Diskagma* has been found in paleosols 2.2 billion years old.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The Neoarchean fossil *Thuchomyces* shares some similarities with fungi.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] It especially resembles the problematic fossil *Diskagma*, with hyphae and multiple differentiated layers.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] However, it is over 600 million years older than all other possible eukaryotes, and many of its "eukaryote features" are not specific to the clade, meaning it is almost certainly a microbial mat instead.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] Structures proposed to represent "large colonial organisms" have been found in the black shales of the Palaeoproterozoic such as the Francevillian B Formation, in Gabon, dubbed the "Francevillian biota" which is dated at 2.1 billion years old.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] However, the status of these structures as fossils is contested, with other authors suggesting that they might represent pseudofossils.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The presence of steranes, eukaryotic-specific biomarkers, in Australian shales previously indicated that eukaryotes were present in these rocks dated at 2.7 billion years old, but these Archaean biomarkers have been rebutted as later contaminants.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The oldest valid biomarker records are only around 800 million years old.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] In contrast, a molecular clock analysis suggests the emergence of sterol biosynthesis as early as 2.3 billion years ago.
[src:acinetactis/eukaryote] The nature of steranes as eukaryotic biomarkers is further complicated by the production of sterols by some bacteria.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The **Global Biodiversity Information Facility** (**GBIF**) is an international organisation that focuses on making scientific data on biodiversity available via the Internet using web services.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The data are provided by many institutions from around the world; GBIF's information architecture makes these data accessible and searchable through a single portal.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] Data available through the GBIF portal are primarily distribution data on plants, animals, fungi, and microbes for the world, and scientific names data.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The mission of the GBIF is to facilitate free and open access to biodiversity data worldwide to underpin sustainable development.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] GBIF strives to form informatics linkages among digital data resources from across the spectrum of biological organisation, from genes to ecosystems, and to connect these to issues important to science, society and sustainability by using georeferencing and GIS tools.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] It works in partnership with other international organisations such as the Catalogue of Life partnership, Biodiversity Information Standards, the Consortium for the Barcode of Life (CBOL), the Encyclopedia of Life (EOL), and GEOSS.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] The biodiversity data available through the GBIF has increased by more than 1,150% in the past decade, partially due to the participation of citizen scientists.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] From 2002 to 2014, GBIF awarded a prestigious annual global award in the area of biodiversity informatics, the Ebbe Nielsen Prize, valued at €30,000.
[src:acinetactis/global-biodiversity-information-facility] As of 2018, the GBIF Secretariat presents two annual prizes: the GBIF Ebbe Nielsen Challenge and the Young Researchers Award.
